tenable.example1: We were finding no common ground, and I was becoming convinced that the marriage was no longer tenable.
tenable.example2: I think this is a perfectly tenable position.
tenable.example3: The time may be approaching when that clever maneuver is no longer tenable.

despotic.example1: The guns seemed to address this country, which invented the streets that secured them with despotic police, in its primary language—violence.
despotic.example2: Now I never had, as the reader knows, either given any formal promise or entered into any engagement; and this language was all much too hard and much too despotic for the occasion.
despotic.example3: The chairs, the carpet, the tables—all had rotted away; they sagged in mutual ruin, victims of the despotic force of time.

radially.example1: Five long chains of brightly colored prayer flags* were then strung radially from the pole above our tents to protect the camp from harm.
radially.example2: Light brown in colour, it has finer and more densely arranged, radially aligned plates called septa and surface ornamentations.
radially.example3: In the inner layer, the fibers extend radially from the periphery of the optic nerve.

roofline.definition: The profile made by a series of roofs

plasticky.definition: Resembling plastic, especially in the sense of being cheap and lightweight.

occlude.definition: To obstruct, cover, or otherwise block (an opening, a portion of an image, etc.).
occlude.example1: Leukocytes become more actively phagocytic, release lysosomal enzymes, turn sticky, and aggregate together in dense masses, occluding capillaries and shutting off the blood supply.
occlude.example2: But deep in the fields the brownish stalks rise from the earth to more than twice her height, occluding her vision.
occlude.example3: I wished still to cry, and attempted it again; and once again, my effort failed, all tears occluded.

garbanzo.definition: An edible pulse, Cicer arietinum, of the family Leguminosae or Fabaceae and subfamilies Faboideae or Papilionoideae, with white or purple-blue flowers and small feathery leaves on both sides of the stem and pods containing two to three peas.
garbanzo.example1: The scent of garbanzo beans in spicy sauce hung in the air, mixed with the smell of dung and sweat.
garbanzo.example2: I’m a big fan of every type of bean, whether cannellini or garbanzo, with a cupboard full of them to choose from.
garbanzo.example3: This colorful spot would become our regular evening haven, where the catch of the day never disappointed, nor did the garbanzo stew.

stringing.example1: Lio has told me that the nickname comes from El Jefe’s childhood habit of stringing bottle caps across his chest to look like medals.
stringing.example2: Even Smith would be in an optimistic, relatively chatty mood, stringing several hundred words together in what the papers would call “a great moral victory for the reporters present.”
stringing.example3: Instead of cheaply stringing dragonflies by the tail, we could fly expensive kites, the sky splendid in Chinese colors, distracting ghost eyes while the new people sneak in.

headwear.definition: A hat or other covering for the head

malachite.definition: A bright green mineral, a basic copper carbonate, Cu2CO3(OH)2; one of the principal ores of copper.
malachite.example1: Here the 10th-century artists painted with ink and brush in rich blues and greens the color of malachite.
malachite.example2: I tipped open a small malachite box whose inventoried contents included a black-and-white passport photo of Kirstein, a Singapore penny, a Canadian dime, a pack of matches and some rolling papers.
malachite.example3: For the Mobiles, she takes elements made in advance and arranges them intuitively and playfully, with raw minerals like pyrite, malachite and amber used for their transformative properties.

extrapolating.definition: To infer by extending known information.
extrapolating.example1: But there are good reasons to be very careful in extrapolating from modern forager societies to ancient ones.
extrapolating.example2: Altogether it is thought–though it is really only a guess, based on extrapolating from cratering rates on the Moon–that some two thousand asteroids big enough to imperil civilized existence regularly cross our orbit.
extrapolating.example3: This principle of ever-more-exact measurement derives from Tycho Brahe; in tightening up the relationship between evidence and theory in physics, Galileo was extrapolating from the practices of the astronomers.

demarcate.definition: To mark the limits or boundaries of something; to delimit.
demarcate.example1: The light flickered over the paper as the old woman crouched down and stared at the lines demarcating the Great Wood, the river Nir, the Kell.
demarcate.example2: From the great plaza radiated four highways that demarcated the four asymmetrical sectors into which he divided the empire, Tawantinsuyu, “Land of the Four Quarters.”
demarcate.example3: She stood looking at the line of trees that demarcated the woods as clearly as any doorway.

atria.definition: A central room or space in ancient Roman homes, open to the sky in the middle; a similar space in other buildings.
atria.example1: My arms are atria and my legs are ventricles and I pump the blood all around the right way because there has to be something I can do.
atria.example2: I found two big atria surrounded by restaurants, theaters, bars, a game room, shops, clubs, an art gallery and a sprawling casino anchored by a two-story-high ribbon-shaped chandelier lit by LEDs that changed color.
atria.example3: Fetuses normally have a hole, or flap, between the left and right atria of the heart that allows blood to flow in between, bypassing the lungs.

pearlescent.definition: Pearl-like, either in color or luster.
pearlescent.example1: This one’s painted in darkly pearlescent greens, blues, and blacks.
pearlescent.example2: Bod could not see her, but there was an extra shadow beneath the hawthorn tree, and, as he approached it, the shadow resolved itself into something pearlescent and translucent in the early-morning light.
pearlescent.example3: The more stylized, pearlescent and unpredictable the text and score, the better; banality creeps in whenever things get more naturalistic.

polemic.definition: A person who writes in support of one opinion, doctrine, or system, in opposition to another; one skilled in polemics; a controversialist; a disputant.
polemic.example1: In Congress, North Carolina senator Sam Ervin Jr. drafted a racist polemic, the “Southern Manifesto,” which vowed to fight to maintain Jim Crow by all legal means.
polemic.example2: I was heart-sick at the prospect that he might want to re-edit the entire book into a polemic against Elijah Muhammad.
polemic.example3: Was it not a word, thanks to Pascal, irretrievably associated with religious polemics of the sort that the members of the Royal Society were determined to avoid?

reportable.example1: Of course, she was the first to speak—intelligibly, I mean, for the emotional remarks which followed her impetuous “Oh, yes!” were not of a coherent or reportable character.
reportable.example2: Sorry to say the gun was far too much to cope with following my first ever reportable prang, in a plane I probably shouldn’t have been flying, and I burst into tears.
reportable.example3: There was that weird incident at the Idle Hour when Brian saw me with Phil, but I don’t think being a jerk qualifies as a reportable offense.

pct.definition: A percentage, a proportion (especially per hundred).
pct.example1: "They travel, they go to cinemas, they go to concerts. I am counting on the middle segment, which is about 80 pct of the population," he said.
pct.example2: "With currency volatility, cash earning next to zero and inflation at 4.5 pct in London, a lot of people are looking at art right now as a safe haven for their money," he said.
pct.example3: Johnny Depp ...........76 pct Below is a list of the top 10 most unpopular personalities with their "unfavorable" rating by percentage of voters.

revocable.definition: Having the ability of being revoked; capable of being revoked.
revocable.example1: It’s a new finality for the man with a license to kill, but, apparently, a revocable permit to live forever.
revocable.example2: “Among other benefits, a revocable trust affords privacy to public figures and celebrities in the administration of their affairs,” she said.
revocable.example3: It’s born of another conflict, between the ownership of physical media and the mere purchase of access to data—between the permanent and the revocable, between the onetime purchase and the monthly subscription forever.

clashed.example1: The sharp north wind clashed the naked branches of the cottonwoods.
clashed.example2: Long before apartheid existed these tribal factions clashed and warred with one another.
clashed.example3: Those symbols of great wealth and the reality of their lives too noisily clashed.

conveying.definition: To move (something) from one place to another.
conveying.example1: A shocking number of phrases that drop easily from the fingers are bloated with words that encumber the reader without conveying any content.
conveying.example2: We live in a sea of images conveying the culture and learning of modern civilization.
conveying.example3: He might be thinking she was talking to him in code, suggestively conveying her taste for the full-blooded and sensual.
